{% include "base.j2" %}

[DATA]
{{ data | tojson(indent=2) }}
[/DATA]

[CHAIN OF THOUGHT]
Before writing findings, reason through the data step by step:
1. Read each Census metric: note direction (slope sign) and reliability (R²). Skip R² < 0.5.
2. Cross-reference: do declining income + high violations + high poverty form a compounding pattern?
3. Check business health: closed rate > 20% signals economic stress.
4. Read deprivation scores: which index is highest? What are the top 3 driving factors?
5. Read workforce data: compare unemployment_rate_pct vs city_avg_unemployment_pct, median_household_income vs city_avg_median_income, bachelors_plus_pct, poverty_rate_pct vs city_avg_poverty_pct. Flag any gap wider than 10 points or income below 70% of city average as a workforce finding.
6. Read citizen_survey_signals: what do residents say are their top priorities? Note alignment or divergence vs. ArcGIS data.
7. Identify 3 to 5 distinct factual findings. Each must cite a specific number from DATA.
   When writing counts of people or buildings in narrative text, round to nearest integer (Census ACS weighted estimates — 207.6 → 208 people). Keep raw decimals for rates, percentages, and dollar amounts.
   At least one finding must reference citizen survey data (e.g. "X of Y survey respondents prioritized...") if survey_signals has respondents > 0.
7. Assign overall severity using quartile thresholds (ADI/SVI standard):
   critical = score > 0.75 on 2+ indices (top quartile, worse than 75% of Montgomery neighborhoods)
   high     = score 0.50–0.75 on 2+ indices (above median)
   moderate = score 0.25–0.50
   low      = score < 0.25
   Business closure rate: > 15% = commercial distress (LISC standard).

[OUTPUT SCHEMA]
{
  "neighborhood": "{{ neighborhood }}",
  "overall_severity": "critical|high|moderate|low",
  "severity_rationale": "One sentence citing the specific scores that justify this rating.",
  "findings": [
    {
      "category": "housing|economy|environment|public_safety|health|infrastructure|workforce|transportation|education|parks_culture|governance",
      "finding": "One factual sentence citing a specific number from DATA.",
      "metric_cited": "variable name",
      "value": "raw value from DATA",
      "trend": "improving|declining|stable|unknown"
    }
  ],
  "strongest_signal": "The single most statistically reliable finding (highest R² or largest z-score deviation).",
  "data_confidence": "high|moderate|low",
  "confidence_note": "Brief note on variables_used vs variables_expected across indices."
}
